<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very distinctive species because of the winged stem, deeply 3-lobed leaves, much-branched, almost paniculate inflorescence and the aristate sepals. The white flowers are reported to be aromatic. Molecular sequencing using 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">ITS</emphasis>
suggests a relationship with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="costellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea costellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its allies but there is little superficial morphological similiarity apart from the aristate sepals and trilobed leaves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
